Minimal fix: add a check `if (target.getType() == Token.STRING) { className = target.getString(); }`. Possibly also check for ADD nodes that eventually reduce to a string? But the minimal fix is to avoid the exception. So:

```java
private static String extractClassNameIfGoog(Node node, Node parent,
    String functionName){
  String className = null;
  if (NodeUtil.isExprCall(parent)) {
    Node callee = node.getFirstChild();
    if (callee != null && callee.getType() == Token.GETPROP) {
      String qualifiedName = callee.getQualifiedName();
      if (functionName.equals(qualifiedName)) {
        Node target = callee.getNext();
        if (target != null && target.getType() == Token.STRING) {
          className = target.getString();
        }
      }
    }
  }
  return className;
}
```

If we want to be more robust, we could also handle ADD nodes to extract the final string, but that might be overkill. The minimal fix is to guard against non-string target.

